<section xml:id="section-assignment-week2">
  <title>Week 2 Assignment</title>
  <p><ol>
    <li>
      <p>
        Prove that all vectors <m>\begin{pmatrix} w \\ x \\ y \\ z
        \end{pmatrix} \in \RR^4</m> which satisfy <m>4w - 2x + 6y + 2z
        = 0 </m> are orthogonal to the vector <m>\frac{1}{2}
        \begin{pmatrix} -2 \\ 1 \\ -3 \\ -1 \end{pmatrix} </m>. (4)
      </p>
    </li>
    <li>
      <p>
        If <m>u</m> and <m>v</m> are vectors in <m>\RR^3</m>, prove
        that 
        <me>
          (u + v) \cdot (u - v) = |u|^2 - |v|^2 
        </me>.
        (4)
      </p>
    </li>
    <li>
      <p>
        The cross product of <m>u</m> and <m>v</m> in <m>\RR^3</m> is
        a new vector which is perpendicular to both <m>u</m> and
        <m>v</m>. Explain why this description of the cross-product can
        only work in three dimensions. If you have to generalize the
        cross-product to higher dimensions, based on this idea of
        generating a new vector perpendicular to the two previous, how
        would you do it? (4)
      </p>
    </li>
    <li>
      <p>
        Find the angle between these pairs of vectors. (You can give
        answers in approximate values. Show the steps in your
        calculation using the definitions from the course.) (9)
        <ol>
          <li><md><mrow>
            \amp \begin{pmatrix}
              4 \\ -1 
            \end{pmatrix},
            \amp \amp 
            \begin{pmatrix}
              2 \\ 2 
            \end{pmatrix}
          </mrow></md></li>
          <li><md><mrow>
            \amp \begin{pmatrix}
              0 \\ -7 \\ 3 
            \end{pmatrix},
            \amp \amp 
            \begin{pmatrix}
              -1 \\ -9 \\ 2 
            \end{pmatrix}
          </mrow></md></li>
          <li><md><mrow>
            \amp \begin{pmatrix}
              -4 \\ 3 \\ 0 \\ 2 \\ -5 
            \end{pmatrix},
            \amp \amp 
            \begin{pmatrix}
              4 \\ 0 \\ -2 \\ -11 \\ 3
            \end{pmatrix}
          </mrow></md></li>
        </ol>
      </p>
    </li>
  </ol></p>
</section>
